[{"id":38971,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Energy liberated is given by, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>∆</mo><mi>m</mi><msup><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced><mo>×</mo><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>8</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>3600</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>7</mn></msup><mo> </mo><mi>kW</mi><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3600</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>7</mn></msup></mrow><mn>3600</mn></mfrac><mo> </mo><mi>kW</mi><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>7</mn></msup><mo> </mo><mi>kW</mi><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">h</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (31 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":38985,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>27</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>eV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>eV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>eV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>54</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>eV</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Energy of Hydrogen like atoms is,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><msup><mi>Z</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mi>eV</mi></math>.</p><p>Since Helium is in the first state,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Z</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math>.</p><p>The energy of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>He</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;ion is,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><msup><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>eV</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (11 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":38956,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["$\\lambda_4 \\lt \\lambda_3 \\lt \\lambda_2 \\lt \\lambda_1$","$\\lambda_3 \\lt \\lambda_4 \\lt \\lambda_2 \\lt \\lambda_1$","$\\lambda_4 \\lt \\lambda_3 \\lt \\lambda_1 \\lt \\lambda_2$","$\\lambda_4 \\lt \\lambda_2 \\lt \\lambda_3 \\lt \\lambda_1$"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6bfhdUw5dOHTZD9PGrbOmkQyMnzDuSiQcSSiqYaTP3Y.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (24 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":38955,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["$\\frac{1}{n^4}$","$\\frac{1}{n^2}$","$\\frac{1}{\\mathrm{n}}$","$\\frac{1}{n^3}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} & f=\\frac{v}{2 \\pi r}=\\left(\\frac{V_0}{n}\\right)\\left(\\frac{1}{2 \\pi r_0 n^2}\\right) \\\\ & f=\\frac{V_0}{2 \\pi r_0}=\\left(\\frac{1}{n^3}\\right)=f_0\\left(\\frac{1}{n^3}\\right)\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (28 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39025,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>&#8733;</mo><mi>n</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>v</mi><mi mathvariant=\"italic\">n</mi></msub><mo mathvariant=\"italic\">&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mn mathvariant=\"italic\">1</mn><mi mathvariant=\"italic\">n</mi></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>v</mi><mi mathvariant=\"italic\">n</mi></msub><mo mathvariant=\"italic\">&#8733;</mo><msup><mi>n</mi><mn mathvariant=\"italic\">2</mn></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>v</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>We know velocity of electron in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>n</mi><mtext>th&#160;</mtext></msup></math> shell of hydrogen atom is given by</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mi>k</mi><mi>Z</mi><msup><mi>e</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mi>v</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>n</mi></mfrac></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (17 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39039,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>7</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>20</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>7</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>9</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>7</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>","<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>27</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<math><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>λ</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>R</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mfrac><mrow><mi>R</mi><mo>×</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>144</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>  <br/><math><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>λ</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>R</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mfrac><mrow><mi>R</mi><mo>×</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>36</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>  <br/><math><mo>⇒</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>λ</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>λ</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>R</mi><mo>×</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>36</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>144</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>R</mi><mo>×</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>20</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>7</mn></mrow></mfrac></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39022,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mi>eV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2815</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>eV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>331</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>eV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>27</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>eV</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>r</mi></mfrac><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>m</mi></mrow></mfrac></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>E</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mi>m</mi></math>. Ionization potential <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mfenced><msub><mtext>Mass</mtext><mi>&#956;</mi></msub></mfenced><mi>eV</mi></mrow><mfenced><msub><mtext>Mass</mtext><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></msub></mfenced></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>207</mn><mi>eV</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2815</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>eV</mi></math>.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39009,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["Both statement I and statement II are true.","Both statement I and statement II are false.","Statement I is correct but statement II is false.","Statement I is incorrect but statement II is true."],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f855a3cf-53b5-48f7-afcd-4df54860504c-image.png\" style=\"width: 130px; height: 136px;\" />&nbsp;</p><p>According to Bohr&#39;s model, when electron makes the transition from lower orbit to higher orbit, its energy can be given as</p><p>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8710;</mo><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>E</mi><mi>final</mi></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>E</mi><mi>initial</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>h</mi><mi>f</mi></math>, here,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>h</mi></math>&nbsp;is Planck&#39;s constant.</p><p>Then,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>f</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow><mi>h</mi></mfrac></math>.</p><p>Bohr&#39;s frequency condition is the law&nbsp;that state that the frequency of the radiation emitted or absorbed during the transition of an atomic system between two stationary states equals the difference in the energies of the states divided by Planck&#39;s constant.</p><p>Hence,&nbsp;Statement I is incorrect but statement II is true.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":38988,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["Zero","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi>L</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>L</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>L</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Bohr&#39;s formula for angular momentum&nbsp;of an electron in an orbit&nbsp;is given by&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>L</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>For the first orbit,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp;and the angular momentum is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>L</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>h</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>L</mi></math></p><p>For&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>2</mn><mi>nd</mi></msup></math>&nbsp;orbit</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>L</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>h</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>L</mi></math></p><p>Hence, the change in angular momentum is&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#916;</mi><mi>L</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>L</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>L</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>L</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (10 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39045,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math><mn>250</mn><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>m</mi></math>","<math><mn>1700</mn><mi> </mi><mi>n</mi><mi>m</mi></math>","<math><mn>220</mn><mi> </mi><mi>n</mi><mi>m</mi></math>","<math><mn>2020</mn><mi> </mi><mi>n</mi><mi>m</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"When electron pass through the mercury vapor, it losses some of its energy. The loss in <math><mi>K</mi><mi>E</mi></math> of electron <math><mo>=</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>5</mn><mo>&#8901;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>0.7</mn></mrow></mfenced><mi>e</mi><mi>V</mi></math> <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>4.9</mn><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>V</mi></math><br /><br /><math><mo>&#8756;</mo></math> energy of radiation emitted <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi>&#160;</mi><mn>4.9</mn><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>V</mi></math><br /><br /><math><mo>&#8756;</mo></math> wavelength of radiation, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#955;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1.24</mn><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mo>&#215;</mo><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>4</mn></msup></mrow><mn>4.9</mn></mfrac><mi>A</mi><mo>&#8776;</mo><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mn>250</mn><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mi>n</mi><mi>m</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":38993,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>In <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Z</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>17</mn></math>&nbsp;and have equal numbers of protons and neutrons i.e. nucleons<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>17</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>34</mn></math></p><p>So, for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi></math>,&nbsp;</p><p>Total binding energy&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><msub><mi>E</mi><mi>A</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>34</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>40</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>MeV</mi></math></p><p>Another nucleus&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi></math> mass number&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>26</mn></math></p><p>So, total binding energy of&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi></math>&nbsp;is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><msub><mi>E</mi><mi>B</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>26</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>MeV</mi></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>46</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>MeV</mi></math></p><p>Difference of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>B</mi><msub><mi>E</mi><mi>B</mi></msub><mo>-</mo><mi>B</mi><msub><mi>E</mi><mi>A</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>MeV</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (01 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":38989,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The formula to calculate the wavelength of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>H</mi><mi>&#945;</mi></msub></math>-line in Balmer series is given by</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>h</mi><mi>c</mi></mrow><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mi>&#945;</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>9</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>The formula to calculate the wavelength of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>H</mi><mi>&#946;</mi></msub></math>-line in Balmer series is given by</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>h</mi><mi>c</mi></mrow><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mi>&#946;</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>16</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>2</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>Divide equation (2) by equation (1)&nbsp;<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mi>&#945;</mi></msub><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mi>&#946;</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>16</mn></mfrac></mrow><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>9</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>36</mn><mn>64</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>12</mn><mn>5</mn></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>27</mn><mn>20</mn></mfrac></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39074,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["$207 \\mathrm{~nm}$","$465 \\mathrm{~nm}$","$310 \\mathrm{~nm}$","$620 \\mathrm{~nm}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"$E=\\frac{h c}{\\lambda}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (12 May Online)","image":null},{"id":39069,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["$n^2$","$n$","$n^{1 / 2}$","$n^{1 / 4}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"According to the question,\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& 2 \\pi \\mathrm{r}=\\mathrm{n} \\lambda=\\frac{\\mathrm{nh}}{\\mathrm{p}}=\\frac{\\mathrm{nh}}{\\mathrm{mv}} \\\\\n& \\text { or } \\mathrm{mvr}=\\frac{\\mathrm{nh}}{2 \\pi} \\text { or } \\mathrm{mv}=\\frac{\\mathrm{nh}}{2 \\pi \\mathrm{r}} \\\\\n& \\mathrm{F}=\\mathrm{qv}_{\\mathrm{B}}=\\frac{\\mathrm{mv}^2}{\\mathrm{r}} \\\\\n& \\text { or, } \\mathrm{q}_{\\mathrm{B}}=\\frac{\\mathrm{mv}}{\\mathrm{r}}=\\frac{\\mathrm{nh}}{2 \\pi \\mathrm{r} \\cdot \\mathrm{r}} \\\\\n& \\text { or, } \\mathrm{r}^2=\\frac{\\mathrm{nh}}{2 \\pi \\mathrm{qB}} \\\\\n& \\text { or, } \\mathrm{r}=\\sqrt{\\frac{\\mathrm{nh}}{2 \\pi \\mathrm{qB}}} \\\\\n& \\text { i.e., } \\mathrm{r} \\propto \\mathrm{n}^{1 / 2}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (22 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":39057,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math><msup><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math><msup><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math><msup><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math><msup><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<math> <mi>v</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac> <mi>z</mi> <mi>n</mi> </mfrac> </math><br /><br /><math> <mi>r</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac> <mrow> <msup> <mi>n</mi> <mn>2</mn> </msup> </mrow> <mi>z</mi> </mfrac> </math><br /><br /><math> <mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac> <mrow> <mi>&#956;</mi><mi>I</mi></mrow> <mrow> <mn>2</mn><mi>R</mi></mrow> </mfrac> </math><br /><br /><math> <mi>I</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac> <mi>e</mi> <mi>T</mi> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo><mfrac> <mi>e</mi> <mrow> <mrow><mo>(</mo> <mrow> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mi>R</mi></mrow> <mi>v</mi> </mfrac> </mrow> <mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo><mfrac> <mi>e</mi> <mrow> <mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow> </mfrac> <mfrac> <mi>v</mi> <mi>R</mi> </mfrac> </math><br /><br /><math> <mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac> <mrow> <msub> <mi>&#956;</mi> <mn>0</mn> </msub> </mrow> <mn>2</mn> </mfrac> <mfrac> <mi>e</mi> <mrow> <mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow> </mfrac> <mfrac> <mi>v</mi> <mrow> <msup> <mi>R</mi> <mn>2</mn> </msup> </mrow> </mfrac> </math><br /><br /><math> <mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac> <mrow> <msub> <mi>&#956;</mi> <mn>0</mn> </msub> <mi>e</mi></mrow> <mrow> <mn>4</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow> </mfrac> <mfrac> <mi>z</mi> <mrow> <mi>n</mi><msup> <mrow> <mrow><mo>(</mo> <mrow> <mfrac> <mrow> <msup> <mi>n</mi> <mn>2</mn> </msup> </mrow> <mi>z</mi> </mfrac> </mrow> <mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow> <mn>2</mn> </msup> </mrow> </mfrac> </math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>e</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac><mfrac><msup><mi>z</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>5</mn></msup></mfrac></math><br /><br /><math> <mi>B</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><msup> <mi>n</mi> <mrow> <mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow> </msup> </math>.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2017 (08 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":38960,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["$3.646 \\times 10^{-6} \\mathrm{~m}$","$1.876 \\times 10^{-6} \\mathrm{~m}$","$2.973 \\times 10^{-6} \\mathrm{~m}$","$1.094 \\times 10^{-6} \\mathrm{~m}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"For longest wavelength in Paschen's series:\n$\\frac{1}{\\lambda}=\\mathrm{R}\\left[\\frac{1}{\\mathrm{n}_1^2}-\\frac{1}{\\mathrm{n}_2^2}\\right]$\nFor longest $\\mathrm{n}_1=3$\n$\\mathrm{n}_2=4$\n$\\begin{aligned} & \\frac{1}{\\lambda}=\\mathrm{R}\\left[\\frac{1}{(3)^2}-\\frac{1}{(4)^2}\\right] \\\\ & \\frac{1}{\\lambda}=\\mathrm{R}\\left[\\frac{1}{9}-\\frac{1}{16}\\right] \\\\ & \\frac{1}{\\lambda}=\\mathrm{R}\\left[\\frac{16-9}{16 \\times 9}\\right] \\\\ & \\Rightarrow \\lambda=\\frac{16 \\times 9}{7 \\mathrm{R}}=\\frac{16 \\times 9}{7 \\times 1.097 \\times 10^7} \\\\ & \\lambda=1.876 \\times 10^{-6} \\mathrm{~m}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (06 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":38967,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["$\\frac{h}{\\pi}$","$\\frac{h}{2 \\pi}$","$8 \\frac{h}{\\pi}$","$2 \\frac{h}{\\pi}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"Moment of momentum is $\\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{r}} \\times \\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{P}}$\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& \\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{L}}=\\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{r}} \\times \\mathrm{m} \\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{v}} \\\\\n& \\mathrm{L}=\\mathrm{mvr}=\\frac{\\mathrm{nh}}{2 \\pi}=\\frac{4 \\mathrm{~h}}{2 \\pi}=\\frac{2 \\mathrm{~h}}{\\pi}\n\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (04 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39030,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>121</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>nm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>194</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>nm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>490</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>nm</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>913</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>nm</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>&#955;</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>R</mi><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#955;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>121</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>nm</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":38976,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["Both statement I and statement II are false","Statement I is false but statement II is true","Statement I is true but statement II is false","Both statement I and statement II are true"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Rutherford proposed that most of the mass of an atom is concentrated in a small, dense nucleus at the centre, which contains positively charged protons. Electrons, carrying negative charge, revolve around the nucleus in orbits.</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In the Bohr model, electrons do not move in random orbits but have specific energy levels or shells around the nucleus. The electrons are not in a \"spherical cloud\" but are found in discrete orbits at fixed distances from the nucleus. Rutherford's model, on the other hand, did not specify the fixed orbits of electrons and was later refined by Bohr to explain the stability of atoms.</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">Hence, statement I is true but statement II is false.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39037,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9acf8be2-3912-4102-8235-9c4f20b5e7d8-image.png\" style=\"width: 203px; height: 205px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/212ce0d9-0285-456b-9cfb-8c6ccb9afd22-image.png\" style=\"width: 203px; height: 205px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9440266f-0f2e-45f5-904d-8482e8549a29-image.png\" style=\"width: 175px; height: 174px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/12447055-b07a-4af2-b33a-e2b149a65b8e-image.png\" style=\"width: 175px; height: 174px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Rutherford carried out an experiment in which he bombarded a thin sheet of gold foil with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#945;</mi></math>-particles and then analysed the trajectory of these particles after they collided with the gold foil.</p><p>For a detector at a specific angle with respect to the incident beam, the number of particles per unit area striking the detector is given by the Rutherford formula,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Y</mi><mfenced><mi>&#952;</mi></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>N</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mi>n</mi><mi>L</mi><msup><mi>Z</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mi>k</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mi>e</mi><mn>4</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mfenced><mrow><mi>K</mi><mi>E</mi></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mi>sin</mi><mn>4</mn></msup><mfenced><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mi>&#952;</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mstyle></mfenced></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>Here,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>N</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo>=</mo></math>&nbsp;Number of incident alpha particles,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo></math>&nbsp;Atoms per unit volume in target,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>L</mi><mo>=</mo></math>&nbsp;Thickness of target,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Z</mi><mo>=</mo></math>&nbsp;Atomic number of target,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>e</mi><mo>=</mo></math>&nbsp;Electron charge,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo></math>&nbsp;Coulomb&#39;s constant,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo></math>&nbsp;Distance between target and detector,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>K</mi><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo></math>&nbsp;Kinetic energy of alpha particles,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#952;</mi><mo>=</mo></math>&nbsp;Scattering angle.</p><p>Therefore,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Y</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><msup><mi>sin</mi><mn>4</mn></msup><mfenced><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mi>&#952;</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mstyle></mfenced></mrow></mfrac></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (08 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39035,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math><mn>24</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"></mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","<math><mn>11.4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"></mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","<math><mn>35.8</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"></mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>","<math><mn>8.6</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"></mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<math><mfrac><mrow><mi>h</mi><mi>c</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>&#955;</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi></mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mi></mi><mn>6</mn><mi>e</mi><mi>V</mi></mrow></mfenced><msup><mrow><mi>z</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mi></mi><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msubsup><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msubsup></mrow></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mi></mi><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msubsup><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msubsup></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math><br /><math><msub><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math><br /><math><msub><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math><br /><math><mfrac><mrow><mi>h</mi><mi>c</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>&#955;</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi></mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>13.6</mn><mi>e</mi><mi>V</mi></mrow></mfenced><mi></mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><msup><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced><mi></mi><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\" separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math><br /><math><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi></mi><mfrac><mrow><mi>h</mi><mi>c</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>&#955;</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi></mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>13.6</mn><mi>e</mi><mi>V</mi></mrow></mfenced><mi></mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>9</mn></mrow></mfenced><mi></mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>8</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>9</mn></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></math><br />Wavelength <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1240</mn><mrow><mn>8</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>13.6</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mtext>nm</mtext></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#955;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>11.39</mn><mtext>&#160;nm</mtext></math>&nbsp;","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (09 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39003,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>4</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>3</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>4</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>:</mo><mn>1</mn></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Energy of an electron in the&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>n</mi><mi>th</mi></msup></math>&nbsp;orbit of a Hydrogen atom is given by,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>E</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>eV</mi></math></p><p>Therefore,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>E</mi><mo>&#8734;</mo></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>E</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":38964,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["r","$\\sqrt{\\mathrm{r}}$","$\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{\\mathrm{r}}}$","$\\frac{1}{\\mathrm{r}}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} & \\mathrm{F}_{\\mathrm{C}}=\\frac{\\mathrm{mv}^2}{\\mathrm{r}} \\\\ & \\frac{\\mathrm{Kq}_1 \\mathrm{q}_2}{\\mathrm{r}^2}=\\frac{\\mathrm{mv}^2}{\\mathrm{r}} \\\\ & \\mathrm{mv}^2 \\mathrm{r}^2=K \\mathrm{~K}_1 \\mathrm{q}_2 \\mathrm{r} \\\\ & \\frac{\\mathrm{L}^2}{\\mathrm{~m}}=K \\mathrm{Kq}_1 \\mathrm{q}_2 \\mathrm{r} \\\\ & \\mathrm{L} \\propto \\sqrt{\\mathrm{r}}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (05 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":38943,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["1550","1217","1875","1784"],"answer":1,"solution":"Smallest wavelength of lyman<br>$\\dfrac{1}{\\lambda} = R\\left(\\dfrac{1}{1^2} - \\dfrac{1}{\\infty^2}\\right)$<br>$R = \\dfrac{1}{\\lambda} = \\dfrac{1}{91} \\text{ nm}^{-1}$<br>$\\lambda_{max}$ for balmer series<br>$n_1 = 2 \\rightarrow n_2 = 3$<br>$\\dfrac{1}{\\lambda_B} = R\\left(\\dfrac{1}{4} - \\dfrac{1}{9}\\right)$<br>$\\dfrac{1}{\\lambda_B} = \\dfrac{1}{91}\\left(\\dfrac{5}{36}\\right)$<br>$\\lambda_B = \\left(\\dfrac{91 \\times 36}{5}\\right) = 655.2 \\text{ nm}$<br>$\\lambda_{max}$ paschen<br>$n_1 = 3 \\rightarrow n_2 = 4$<br>$\\dfrac{1}{\\lambda_p} = \\dfrac{1}{91}\\left(\\dfrac{1}{3^2} - \\dfrac{1}{4^2}\\right) = \\dfrac{1}{91} \\times \\dfrac{7}{144}$<br>$\\lambda_p = \\left(\\dfrac{91 \\times 144}{7}\\right) = 1872 \\text{ nm}$<br>$\\Delta\\lambda = \\lambda_P - \\lambda_B = 1872 - 655.2$<br>$\\Delta\\lambda = 1216.8$<br>$\\Delta\\lambda \\approx 1217$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (22 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39062,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["kinetic energy and total energy decrease but potential energy increases","its kinetic energy increases but potential energy and total energy decrease","kinetic energy, potential energy and total energy decrease","kinetic energy decreases, potential energy increases but total energy remains same"],"answer":1,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>U</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>e</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mrow><mn>4</mn><msub><mi>&#960;&#949;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>r</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>U</mi></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo></math> potential energy,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>K</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>e</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mrow><mn>4</mn><msub><mi>&#960;&#949;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>r</mi></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></math>=kinetic energy.&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>U</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>K</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>e</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mrow><mn>8</mn><msub><mi>&#960;&#949;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>r</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi></math>=total energy<math><mo>&#8756;</mo></math>&nbsp;As electron de-excites from an excited state to ground state,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>K</mi></math>&nbsp;increases, but&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>U</mi></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi></math> decrease.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2015 (04 Apr)","image":null},{"id":38979,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>In the Paschen radiation series, the longest wavelength corresponds to the transition between <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math>.</p><p>The formula for the wavelength in the given transition can be written as, </p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>λ</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>R</mi><msup><mi>Z</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msubsup><mi>n</mi><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msubsup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>From equation (1), it follows that</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>λ</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>R</mi><msup><mi>Z</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mn>1</mn></mstyle><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msup><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mstyle></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mn>1</mn></mstyle><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msup><mn>4</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mstyle></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mi>R</mi><msup><mi>Z</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mn>1</mn></mstyle><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mn>9</mn></mstyle></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mn>1</mn></mstyle><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mn>16</mn></mstyle></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>7</mn><mi>R</mi><msup><mi>Z</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>9</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>16</mn></mrow></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>⇒</mo><mi>λ</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>144</mn><mrow><mn>7</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p> Hence, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>α</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>144</mn></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (27 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39053,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>34</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>eV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>20</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>eV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>79</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>eV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>109</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>eV</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"The energy is required to remove <math> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>e</mtext> <mo>&#8722;</mo> </msup> </mrow> </math> from singly ionized helium atom<math><mo>=</mo><mi>&#160;</mi><mn>54.4</mn><mi>&#160;</mi><mn>e</mn><mn>V</mn></math>. The energy required to remove <math> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>e</mtext> <mo>&#8722;</mo> </msup> </mrow> </math> from&nbsp;a helium atom <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi>x</mi><mi>&#160;eV</mi></math>, given <math><mn>54.4&#160;</mn><mn>e</mn><mn>V</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>2.2&#160;</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>24.73</mn><mi>&#160;</mi><mn>e</mn><mn>V</mn></math>. The energy required to ionize helium atom <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi>&#160;</mi><mn>79.13</mn><mi>&#160;</mi><mn>e</mn><mn>V</mn><mo>&#8776;</mo><mn>79</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>eV</mi></math>.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr)","image":null},{"id":39015,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<p>In the ground state of Rutherford&#39;s model electrons are in stable equilibrium. While in Thomson&#39;s model electrons always experience a net-force.</p>","<p>An atom has a nearly continuous mass distribution in a Rutherford&#39;s model but has a highly non-uniform mass distribution in Thomson&#39;s model</p>","A classical atom based on Rutherford&#39;s model is doomed to collapse.","The positively charged part of the atom possesses most of the mass in Rutherford&#39;s model but not in Thomson&#39;s model."],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>According to Rutherford&#39;s model, most of the mass of the atom is concentrated at the centre (nucleus) and the electron revolves around it.</p><p>As the electron is moving in a circular motion, it is accelerated. According to Maxwell accelerated charged particle loses its energy in the form of electro-magnetic radiation.</p><p>Therefore, a classical atom based on Rutherford&#39;s model is doomed to collapse.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (24 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39038,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math><mn>1.6</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>14</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math><mn>7.8</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>14</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math><mn>6.2</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>15</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math><mn>5.6</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>12</mn></mrow></msup></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><math><mi>T</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mi>z</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>z</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mi>z</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mi></mi></mrow></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msubsup><mi>n</mi><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></msubsup><msubsup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></msubsup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>8</mn></mfrac></math><br /><math><msub><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn><msub><mrow><mi>T</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub></math></p><p>now,<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>f</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac></mrow></msub></math>&nbsp;<br /><math><msub><mrow><mi>f</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>12.8</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>16</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#8776;</mo><mn>7.8</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>14</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (07 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39023,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["Brackett series","Paschen series","Lyman series","Balmer series"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>The transition from higher states to&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp;lead to the&nbsp;emission of radiation with wavelengths&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>656</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>nm</mi></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>365</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>nm</mi><mo>.</mo></math> These wavelengths fall in the visible region and constitute the Balmer series.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (17 Mar Shift 2)","image":null}]